SENTIMENTAL JOURNEY<br>
El Toro Marine Corps Air Base<br>
El Toro, California<br>
1230 Hours, Tuesday, June 13, 1967<br><br>
…….We boarded the plane and at precisely 1300 hours the front doors were shut tight and the plane began to taxi. <br>
We were welcomed aboard by a beautiful stewardess, Susan Cagey, an attractive twenty-two year old brunette with a slender body and foxy light brown eyes. She spoke with a southern accent that accentuated her femininity. Later, after having been propositioned so often, she promised a date to the first Marine that would call her upon completion of our thirteen month tour of duty. <br>
I pocketed the small Bible I had been given by the elderly gentleman.  Later,  I would place it in my flak-jacket's outside left breast pocket and carry it there for the duration of  my Viet Nam tour. Bullet stoppers was what they were called, and some did indeed stop a bullet or shrapnel and thereby saved a soldiers life. Besides the cookies, the Bibles and the Kool-Aid, the good Samaritans had uttered some words of encouragement and quoted some scriptures. I wished then that I could remember what the old man had said or know where to find those words in the little black book.  <br>
About an hour later everyone was dozing off while watching the in-flight movie or listening to the stereo music coming in through our headsets. I switched  the music control knob on the armrest to the number one listening position just as the plane leveled off and the Captain announced that we would be cruising at an altitude of  twenty-two thousand feet.  The plane made a slight left turning movement and we headed off in a southwesterly direction.  Over my headset I could hear Barry Manilow beginning to sing &quot;Sentimental Journey.&quot; <br><br>
The following story appeared in The Washington Times today, and I wanted to share it with everyone.<br>
  <br><br>
 Women to share stories of Vietnam<br><br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
By Jaclyn LaPlaca<br>
THE WASHINGTON TIMES<br>
November 11, 1997<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
 Thirty years have passed since Helen Tennant Hegelheimer last made the 17-hour flight from the United States to Vietnam. <br>
As a 23-year-old strawberry blond, blue-eyed stewardess, she helped transport thousands of fresh GIs -- every day watching the &quot;boys&quot; walk off the Boeing 707 ramp into war. <br>
. . . . Then the jet would load up again, this time taking veterans back to the United States -- another 17-hour flight, another planeful of faces, these drained of youth.<br>
. . . . Now 53, Mrs. Hegelheimer regrets that she was never able to find a &quot;returnee&quot; -- she doesn't know that any of the men she escorted to the war returned home safely.<br>
. . . . &quot;We're all looking for it,&quot; says Mrs. Hegelheimer, now a grandmother of five, of her quest for survivors. &quot;We need to know that someone we helped is living.&quot;<br>
. . . . As part of her search, she traveled from her Sunnyvale, Calif., home to Washington this Veterans Day to participate in today's story-telling program called &quot;Vietnam: In Their Own Words.&quot;<br>
. . . . A dozen women will gather at the base of the Vietnam Women's Memorial from 9 a.m. to 4 p.m. to tell their war stories. They will tell sad stories and cry. They will tell funny tales and chuckle. But mostly the women who went to Vietnam as nurses, Red Cross workers and civilians want to share their memories and ease old hurts.<br>
. . . . The second annual event is just one of thousands of ways Americans will mark today's holiday honoring the men and women who served in the armed forces.<br>
. . . . As she did four years ago when she came to Washington for the dedication of the women's memorial, Mrs. Hegelheimer will place a U.S. flag and a South Vietnamese flag in the upturned helmet that is part of the monument. The statue depicts three women caring for a wounded soldier.<br>
. . . . &quot;This day gives all those who were affected by war a chance to voice their silence,&quot; said the program's organizer, Marsha A. Guenzler-Stevens. &quot;We must remember our history.&quot;<br>
. . . . Mrs. Hegelheimer says she was a civilian &quot;round-eyed stew&quot; for World Airways, a privately owned company that contracted with the federal government to transport soldiers to Vietnam and back. She's eager to share her memories of the 165 men she met on each flight.<br>
. . . . She can still hear and feel the silence and tension on the airplanes; the guilt she continues to feel for not telling the soldiers what they truly faced. She recalls stealing milk for &quot;her fellas&quot; on their homeward flights and how they nicknamed her &quot;Freedom Bird.&quot; She can still feel the relief of her jet clearing Vietnamese airspace and leaving behind the gunfire that pelted even commercial flights.<br>
. . . . And then she watched the veterans come back stateside, jumping from the fourth step of the ramp to kiss American ground, only to be greeted by protesters.<br>
. . . . &quot;I always prayed for a band or parade to meet the heroes,&quot; she says. &quot;These guys weren't going back to their girlfriends, baseball games and '57 Chevies, but I couldn't tell them that.&quot;<br>
. . . . There were the men who asked her to practice speaking with them on the flight, because they were afraid of swearing in front of their mothers. And the soldiers returning to Vietnam who asked her to visit their wounded friends at home. Mrs. Hegelheimer spent one flight holding the hand of a soldier whose wife was in labor at home -- and later she got to visit the baby.<br>
. . . . &quot;I still have nightmares almost every night, but I'd do it again in a New York second,&quot; she says of her experiences.<br>
. . . . Margaret Kieran Good of Waterford, Va., said she will share her story out of a sense of duty.<br>
. . . . &quot;Some of us will tell sad stories and cry,&quot; said Mrs. Waterford, who will speak about her years with the American Red Cross in Vietnam providing recreation for the men at the fire-bases. &quot;But I was the first Vanna White, so I have to make people smile.&quot;<br>
. . . . By reminiscing about the &quot;Jeopardy&quot; board games, cajoling battle-hardened soldiers into relaxing by pushing peanuts across tabletops with their noses, or by singing, Mrs. Good said she wants to be respectful of the dead while enjoying being with the living.<br>
. . . . Evangeline Jamison is a &quot;lifer&quot; who served as an Army nurse in World War II, Korea and Vietnam -- and will be visiting all the war monuments today. She has visited Washington every Memorial Day and Veterans Day for the past 30 years, but the plane ride from her home in Walnut Creek, Calif., is beginning to wear on the 77-year-old.<br>
. . . . She said she comes to share her stories and raise funds for the Women's Memorial, which still owes $500,000 for the statue.<br>
. . . . &quot;As long as I am able to come, I will,&quot; Mrs. Jamison said. &quot;And it's fun -- men who I've never seen before kiss me and thank me for my service.&quot;<br>
